Description: Typical range for industrial 1064 nm pulsed laser cleaning of reflective metals like tin to balance efficiency and avoid melting (tin melting point ~232°C); starting at 100W for light contamination. Max safe ~300-500W with proper pulsing to prevent substrate damage due to high reflectivity (~70% at 1064 nm). Source: Manufacturer specs (e.g., IPG Photonics YLR series for metal cleaning); academic review in 'Laser Cleaning' by Kononenko et al. (Optics & Lasers in Engineering, 2016).
Near-IR wavelength for efficient Tin oxide absorption with minimal substrate heating
Beam spot diameter for precise Tin surface cleaning
Optimal repetition rate for efficient Tin cleaning with thermal management
Nanosecond pulse duration for controlled Tin oxide ablation
Optimal scanning speed for uniform Tin oxide removal
Recommended number of passes for complete Tin oxide removal
Optimal beam overlap for uniform Tin surface cleaning
